TRANSCRIPTION_TRANSLATION.translation: My child constantly argues. What to do? First, understand that they have a need to feel worthy, to survive, and thereby compete to have the last word. To help the child, we must both satisfy the need and teach communication skills, but only by our own example. So, we must calm ourselves down, and even if the child says something we disagree with, we should simply say, I can't agree with that. But, in any case, let's observe, read, think a little more about it, and we will talk about it later. Similarly, we often reinforce if the child asks us questions, saying, it pleases me so much when you are interested in my opinion, and we say that we are pleased when the child agrees with something. Over time, the child will learn.

TRANSLATION.translation: My child is constantly arguing, what to do? üí≠ "I don't want to do this," "She can, but I can't!" "But I want to!" Don't know how to react? In our video, we explain how to avoid arguments and build a dialogue with children. Also, pay attention to these points: üëâ Stay calm Children often test boundaries, and your reaction will help them understand how to behave properly. üëâ Listen to the child before responding Your attention to their opinion will help them feel understood. üëâ Openly talk about your beliefs using constructive communication "I understand your point of view, but here's why I think so..." üëâ Ask the child why they think this way It will help them realize their position and find a compromise üëâ Encourage constructive conversations and actions üëâ Praise the child for wanting to express their opinion üëâ If the argument crosses the line, clearly but calmly explain that some rules are non-negotiable If you need psychological support in Poland, put "+" in the comments and we will share the information. Spilno üëà

messages.VIDEO_SUMMARY: The video features a woman addressing the camera, discussing various aspects of communication and understanding emotional needs within family dynamics, particularly focusing on addressing conflicts and valuing children's perspectives. She emphasizes the importance of listening, even when disagreements occur, and highlights the role of teaching communication skills through personal example. The woman repeatedly underscores the value of understanding children's needs together, as encapsulated in the recurring message, "It's easier to understand children together!"
